Nigerian student Moshood Adisa Olabisi Ajala wearing an agbada and an Igbo Ozo cap, sits astride the motor scooter on which he is making a round-the-world trip, in Berlin, Germany. Ajala's trip is set to take him through Poland to Moscow and onto Beijing, with the countries visited written on the scooter's bodywork. At the time this photo was taken, Olabisi Ajala was 28 years old, as a student in the US, he battled with depression and attempted suicide twice, but took fate into his own hands. Ajala lived his life on the edge. He was a journalist, travel writer, actor, and later Lagos socialite. He is famous for being a globe-trotter, with escapades in Israel, Egypt, Palestine, India, the United States, and elsewhere. His only published book, which covered his travel adventures, was titled An African Abroad published in 1963. On April 27, 1957, Ã€jÃ lÃ¡ began a trip "around the world" from London. These would form the basis for his 1963 biography called "An African Abroad", with an introduction by Tom Mboya. He planned to visit forty countries. Ã€jÃ lÃ¡ had visited India, the Soviet Union, Iran, Jordan, Israel, Palestine, Egypt, and finally, Australia. He travelled round all of them on his Vespa scooter, which had famous autographs of the famous people he had met. On his journey around the world, he met many more, among whom were Jawaharlal Nehru, Golda Meir, Abubakar Tafawa Balewa, Gamal Abdel Nasser, The Shah of Iran, and Nikita Khrushchev. He also visited Poland, Germany, Prague, Czechoslovakia, Austria, Yugoslavia, Albania, Bulgaria, Rumani, Hungary, and Turkey While living in Lagos, Ã€jÃ lÃ¡ suffered a stroke in the early days of 1999around and did not receive adequate care. He died on February 2, 1999. PUBLIC APOLOGY OF MISS ISHI LEI FLORES BAYSA Kahapon, mahigit sa 10,000 katao ang nagtipon sa Cotabato City Plaza upang magkaisa sa panalangin para sa kalayaan ng Palestine. Ngunit isang mamamayan, si Miss Ishi Lei Flores Baysa, isang 20-taong gulang na babae, ang kumuha ng larawan ng pagtitipon at sinabi, "Edi sana sumugod kayo sa Israel. Nagpapatraffic lang kayo dito sa Cotabato City." Agad kumalat ang kanyang post at siya ay pinagbuhatan ng kamay online. Ngayong araw, nagtungo siya kay Mayor Para sa Lahat Bruce Matabalao upang mag-public apology. . Kasama niya ang pagsisisi at determinasyon na itama ang kanyang pagkakamali. Sa kanilang pag-uusap, ipinaabot ni Mayor Matabalao ang mahalagang mga payo sa lahat. Pinahalagahan niya ang pagiging responsable sa paggamit ng social media at pagpapakita ng respeto sa kapwa. Binigyang diin niya na ang pagpapatawad ay isang daan patungo sa pagkakaisa at kapayapaan. Naniniwala si Mayor Matabalao na sa pagkakamali ni Miss Baysa, mayroong mahalagang aral na dapat matutunan para sa lahat. Ang pag-unlad at pagbabago ay nagsisimula sa pagtanggap ng pagkukulang at pagiging bukas sa pag-unlad ng bawat isa.

For most people, buying their first house is an important milestone. They have to work hard to save up, making it one of the most significant purchases of their lives, and for some, it can take decades to pay it off. In order to turn a house into a home, it takes countless hours of organization, time, and effort to make it unique and a reflection of their character and preferences. The home becomes a sanctuary and a place of refuge, away from the stresses of the outside world. Family homes that people inherit have an even deeper sense of value as they represent generations of family bonds, memories, and a connection to the past. They serve as a way to keep the memories of deceased family members alive and provide a sense of connection. After the arduous effort of building your own home or inheriting a family home, imagine if someone tried to force you out. What would be your reaction? How would you respond if someone came at gunpoint and told you to leave, claiming the house is theirs? What if they threatened to harm your family, or worse, actually harmed your spouse and children to make you submit to their will? Would you surrender, handing over your keys and giving up what is rightfully yours? Or would you fight with every ounce of your existence to protect your property and your family? How unjust would you consider the person who is forcing you out of the home you worked so hard to build? How would you feel if, after your family members were brutally killed, you were forced out of your house, and the media portrayed you as the oppressor, while your home, heritage, and existence were all stolen from you? How would you react? This is the harsh reality for the Palestinians in Gaza over the past 75 years. They have been forced out of their homes, terrorized, harassed, and even murdered. When they attempt to resist this oppression, they are often condemned. While we support their resistance, we do not support any acts that are condemnable Israel is one of the most powerful armies in the world and they are attacking unarmed civilians. 2000 people are already dead and over a million people are displaced. Please support our brothers and sisters in Palestine by donating and praying for them. #Palestine #FreePalestine

Russian President Vladimir Putin has entered the fevered diplomatic fray of the Middle East. Russian President Vladimir Putin spoke to five of the major players, including Iran and the leading Arab powers, in an attempt to secure a ceasefire in the war between Israel and Hamas. Meanwhile, Malaysia has rejected West's 'pressuring attitude' to condemn the Gaza-based Hamas group. .Canadian PM Justin Trudeau is facing flak over his latest statement on the Israel-Palestine war. Trudeau in a new statement expressed concern over the 'dire humanitarian situation' in Gaza. Watch this to know more.

An Israeli air strike has hit al-Ahli hospital in Gaza City where thousands of civilians are seeking medical treatment and shelter from relentless attacks. A UN-run school housing refugees also struck. Sayu dan meremang melihat kekejaman yang berlaku di Palestine. Frontliners disana juga tidak terkecuali menjadi mangsa termasuk kehilangan keluarga tercinta Anda hanya perlu menjadi seorang MANUSIA untuk membantah kekejaman rejim zionis terhadap penduduk Palestine. Penduduk Palestin hidup di bawah pendudukan yang paling KEJAM dan lama dalam sejarah moden. Mereka merampas tanah dan air mereka; memusnahkan rumah, perniagaan dan tanaman mereka; memindahkan penduduk; membunuh orang awam termasuk kanak kanak kanak. Berikan sokongan dan teruskan berdoa agar mereka diberi kekuatan untuk menempuh dugaan berat ini.

The first step toward peace - if anyone has any concern for the Israeli hostages and the families of the victims of terror attacks, the 500,000 Gazan civilians now bombed out of their homes, the over 1000 Gazan children killed by airstrikes, the thousands of innocent pregnant women and civilians in hospitals now without access to water or food - is an immediate ceasefire. Withdrawal of all U.S. support. No genocide in our names, on our watch, with our tax dollars and weapons. Please call 626-414-5083 That number will call all your representatives automatically. Please politely but clearly ask for an immediate ceasefire and total withdrawal of US support for ethnic cleansing. And an end to US support for apartheid. For peace in Palestine and Israel, and America and the world all human beings needs basic human rights. If this concept is triggering to you, please revisit the page. I am going to start posting much-needed fellow Jewish voices, in support of the uncontroversial Palestinian cause of freedom and dignity, against terrorism (of any kind) and apartheid. "It is evident today in the West that one's political affiliation makes little difference when it comes to Palestine and the Palestinian struggle. To truly understand this moral meltdown, it is essential to place this collective western response within a broader context. The western world is grappling with a significant 'mental breakdown' in the wake of the ongoing global redistribution of power, which is shifting away from the Euro-American sphere. This response is quite understandable because relinquishing centuries-old colonial privileges and licence to dominate non-European nations and the world is undeniably challenging. Today, the western establishment and its mainstream media have returned to the Euro-colonial and racist foundations which underpinned the licence to invade, settle, and commit genocide in the Americas and elsewhere in the world since 1492. It is hardly surprising that the official western stance has wholeheartedly embraced the Israeli settler-colonial narrative, which is essentially an imitation of the original Euro-modern/colonial discourse." The decolonial process isnâ€™t a request. Itâ€™s a wake up call. Itâ€™s jarring. Itâ€™s inconvenient. Itâ€™s also full of deep medicine

I recall getting my ass handed to me during early stages of â€œgetting politicizedâ€ 15+ yrs ago. It was excruciating to â€œnot knowâ€ so much. Call it indoctrination, ego, coloniality, the psychology doctoral process. All I know is I felt both like I was floating towards answers & drowning at once. My best teachers came from elders & youth from the global South really providing a gentle mirror into the power I held- + where I had none. I felt protected & held in ways I never have in my psych â€œeducation.â€ I became more aware of my neoliberal education & the ways colonization impacted me. 

I soon became so sick of over intellectualizing- that I re-turned to my ancestral medicine. Learned about physical AND spiritual combat. It didnâ€™t sit well with me having to choose btw the psychological, spiritual or political. I donâ€™t think we have too. 

Change comes from understanding the root cause of dis-ease. Nothing happens in isolation. As Angela Davis reminds us, â€œwhen we see the police repressing protestors in Ferguson we canâ€™t forget the connections & Israeli army in Palestine.â€ Our struggles are interconnected. 

As a former practicing psychologist for 20+ years I can promise you that the battle wages on in both mind & body. No one wants to really talk about mental health. Not really. We want to â€œeradicate it.â€ Without looking at what kind of binary, pathologizing thinking has lead to the actions. 

We donâ€™t go through literal mobilizations of global decolonization- and not feel it!  We donâ€™t watch /hear the atrocity without our own colonial soul wound being kicked up. Ratusan orang tewas dalam ledakan besar di Rumah Sakit Al-Ahli al-Arabi di Kota Gaza pada Selasa (17/10), yang menjadi tempat berlindung warga selama perang antara Israel dan Hamas.

Pelaku ledakan belum bisa diverifikasi secara independen.

Kementerian Kesehatan di Gaza, yang dikelola Hamas, klaim serangan udara Israel sebagai penyebab ledakan yang menewaskan sekitar 500 orang tersebut.

Sementara militer Israel katakan ledakan tersebut disebabkan oleh peluncuran roket yang gagal oleh kelompok militan Jihad Islam Palestina.

Jubir Jihad Islam Palestina menyangkal pernyataan militer Israel, menyebutnya sebagai 'kebohongan dan dibuat-buat' kepada kantor berita Reuters.

"Biar seluruh dunia tahu, bahwa teroris barbar dari Gaza yang menyerang rumah sakit di Gaza, bukan IDF (militer Israel). Mereka yang membunuh anak-anak kami, juga membunuh anak-anak mereka," tulis PM Israel Benjamin Netanyahu di media sosial X.

Memprotes serangan ini, Presiden Palestina Mahmoud Abbas membatalkan pertemuannya dengan Presiden AS Joe Biden di Yordania pada Rabu (18/10), yang juga akan dihadiri raja Yordania dan presiden Mesir.

Menurut laporan Reuters, ledakan ini menjadi insiden paling mematikan di Gaza sejak awal perang Israel-Hamas pada 7 Oktober lalu.

Our hearts ache today, and our eyes tear up for what's happening in Gaza. More than 500 casualties among innocent civilians, people who dreamed of a better tomorrow, gone in the blink of an eye. A place that should be a haven for the sick and wounded, a hospital, has become a space of pain and sorrow. The shock and pain we feel deepen our fear for our families and siblings there. Words won't do justice to what's happening, and our tears won't bring back those we've lost.

Here, we appeal to all free people of the world and conscious hearts, don't stand idly by. The innocent civilians and the impoverished in Gaza need your protection and voice. Let justice and human rights prevail over politics and interests. We pray from our hearts that God protects everyone in Gaza, grants patience to the hearts of those who have lost loved ones, and restores safety and peace to every inch of Palestine.

28 Conflicts

You Fight, WE Cry- 

28 Conflicts Nft Art Poem-

Oh, the world is torn apart, By twenty-eight conflicts, Each one a burning scar, On humanity's heart. 

In Ukraine, bombs fall, And innocent lives are lost, While Israel and Palestine, Fight a battle that costs. 

Syria, Yemen, Afghanistan, The list goes on and on, Conflicts that tear families apart, And leave children all alone. 

Why do we shoot at each other, Instead of shooting for the stars? Why do we hate each other, Because of our colors or our scars? We all bleed the same ink red, No matter our race or creed, So why can't we put aside our differences, And plant a lovelier seed? 

It's 2024, and we still fight for land, Bringing up metal walls, When we should be holding each other's hands. Dejavu once again, the broken world record replays. 

The alarm clock rings, a piercing sound, Time to wake up, time to be found. I open my eyes, look up to the sky, And say thank you, for another day to try. 
I live to fight another day, To gain land, to find my way. 

But why? I ask myself, as I look in the mirror, All I see is a monster, a creature of fear. So I start today, I put my shields down, I put all my metal on the ground. 

I go to my neighbor, and say, "I'm here, How can I help? How can I bring cheer?" I'm tired of fighting, tired of being afraid, I'm ready to build, a world that's well-made. I'm ready to love, to give and to share, To show the planet, that we can all care. 

Dear mirror I got a confession to make, I want you to know, I won't grow, if I don't make this change. so i need to finally say this naked, I love you.

Dear Friends,

Today, I speak to you with a heart heavy as lead, struggling to hold back tears. In Palestine, a human tragedy is unfolding that defies comprehension.

In just the past week, over 6,000 bombs have shattered the fragile peace of this region, more than what the entire United States dropped on Afghanistan in a year. Families have been torn from their homes, and now, two million souls are huddled together in an overcrowded corner of Gaza. The one route of escape, the Egyptian border, has been cruelly reduced to rubble.

Palestine, already stripped of electricity and water, now faces the insufferable agony of white phosphorus contamination. Hospitals overflow with the wounded and the deceased, and they've even asked to evacuate the hospitals. But how can they evacuate with casualties, including tiny babies? The very places meant to provide healing have become targets themselves.

Ambulance vans, once symbols of salvation, have become targets as well. The roads are lined with lifeless bodies, and there's no space left to provide them a dignified resting place.
Even a warehouse of the International Aid Campaign(IAC), a beacon of hope in the darkest of times, has not been spared the wrath of violence.

What cuts deepest is the knowledge that we seem to have learned nothing from our shared history. The world stands by, silent witnesses to this suffering. It's not about religion; it's about our shared humanity.

This, dear friends, is not just a conflict; it is a desperate cry for empathy and compassion. We must stand together, across all borders and beliefs, to demand an immediate end to this devastating crisis.

Posted @withregram â€¢ @middleeasteye A prominent ultra-Orthodox Israeli journalist has gone into hiding after his home was attacked by a mob of far-right Israelis, who targeted him in response to expressions of solidarity with Palestinians under bombardment in Gaza.

The crowd of far-right Israelis surrounded Israel Freyâ€™s home on Saturday night, firing flares into the sky and threatening to kill him.

Frey, who is a Middle East Eye contributor, had openly criticised Israeli policies in the Gaza Strip, where more than 2,750 Palestinians have been killed in air strikes in 10 days, and even recited the Kaddish Jewish mournersâ€™ prayer for Gazaâ€™s women and children.

More than 724 of those killed are children and over 458 women.

The crowd shouted â€œtraitorâ€ several times and told neighbours in the ultra-Orthodox Tel Aviv suburb of Bnei Brak that they should not accept a â€œmurdererâ€ in their building the same way they would not accept a secular person.

After Frey managed to evacuate his children without police support, officers eventually came to his home to escort him at around 2:30am.

According to Haaretz, Frey said a police officer intentionally spat on him as they were heading downstairs, and he was accused of supporting Hamas while being driven to his car. Israeli police then denied this claim to the newspaper.

According to him, the protesters were ultra-Orthodox followers of far-right rabbi Meir Kahane. Kahane was the founder of ultranationalist group Kahane Chai, which was removed from the United Statesâ€™ list of â€œforeign terrorist organizationsâ€ last year.

The attack on Freyâ€™s home comes as Israel considers suppressing voices critical of its policies and actions in the war in Gaza, and critical media organisations and anti-Zionist Jewish citizens have faced increased threats.

Fighting began on 7 October, when hundreds of Palestinian fighters staged a surprise offensive on Israel from Gaza, backed by thousands of rockets. Around 1,400 Israelis were killed in the Hamas-led attack, with Israel saying 199 more Israelis were taken to Gaza as hostages.

The United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees (UNRWA) is no longer able to provide aid to the civilians of the besieged Gaza Strip, amid a deepening dearth of fuel, clean water and medical supplies, spokesperson Tamara Alrifai told CNBC.

â€œAs we speak, UNRWA, the largest aid agency in Gaza, is no longer able to assist and protect civilians, especially those who have taken shelter in our schools and in our buildings. We do not have the supplies, we do not have water, clean drinking water, we do not have food, we do not have hygiene kits,â€ she said, noting that UNWRA staff have lost the ability to move freely on Gaza territories without fear of being targeted.

The 140-square-mile enclave has been under siege by Israel since the start of last week, following a terror attack perpetuated by Palestinian militant group Hamas. Fifteen UNRWA staff members have been killed in the Gaza Strip since the start of hostilities, Alrifai said.

More Palestinian children were killed in the first few days of Israeli attacks on Gaza than Ukrainian children in 18 months since Russiaâ€™s invasion of Ukraine.

Though I follow many international developments closely, this stunned me.

American television viewers have routinely been told that Russiaâ€™s attack on Ukraine is extremely brutal.

How much worse must be the brutality meted out to Palestinian children to have all this death packed into a matter of days as the Western media fail to convey the full horror of what is happening in Gaza and how quickly.

According to the Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights (OHCHR) regarding Ukraine, as of 5 October, it had â€œverified that 9,806 civilians, including 560 children, have been killed as a result of the war. The Office has also verified that 17,962 people, including 1,196 children, have been injured.â€

Defense for Children International - Palestine reported Monday afternoon that already more than 1,000 children have been killed in Gaza.

Defense for Children International - Palestine reports an average of one child killed every 15 minutes since the initiation of the 7 October attack by Hamas â€“ and perhaps other groups â€“ beyond the Gaza boundary that killed soldiers, police and civilians alike.

This figure from DCIP raises profound concerns of just how horrifying the situation in Gaza must be.

And itâ€™s probably worse than the figures cited by DCIP as the organization itself notes.

According to DCIP, Gazaâ€™s Ministry of the Interior reports that over 1,000 people are thought to be buried in rubble and not yet located. That likely means hundreds more children have been killed and not yet added to the overall count.

With children comprising 50 percent of Gazaâ€™s population, roughly one child in 1,000 has been killed.

The summit, to be held in Cairo on Saturday, October 21st,  aims to bring together regional and international partners to find a path towards resolving the crisis.

Hamas, which staged an attack on Israel nearly a week ago and has fired thousands of rockets since, dismissed the evacuation order as a ploy and called on people to stay in their homes.

Weekly Muslim prayers brought protests over the violence in a number of countries including Afghanistan.

Israel has bombarded Gaza round-the-clock since Hamas' attack, in which its fighters massacred hundreds in southern Israel and snatched some 150 people to Gaza as hostages.

The conflict has already claimed over 3,000 lives on both sides and sent tensions soaring across the region.

Protesters carried banners declaring that Israel was the biggest terrorist with one protester demanded that Afghanistan provide "facilities for us to go to Palestine to help our Palestinian brothers and we want to sacrifice ourselves and we want to get  martyrdom against Jewish and Israel."

STORYLINE:
A protest took place in the Libyan capital of Tripoli on Friday denouncing Israel's bombardment of the Gaza Strip that has left civilians and children dead or homeless. 

The protestors came out from several areas in the capital with Palestinian flags and banners, in a march that started in Algiers Square and reached Martyrs Square in the center of the city.

The protestors called on thei government, political parties and citizens to support the Palestinian cause to end the conflict.

Nearly 2.3 million Palestinians live in the Gaza Strip and are cut off from the world. 

The Israeli military has pulverized large parts of the Hamas-ruled Gaza Strip with airstrikes and blocked deliveries of food, water, fuel and electricity ahead of a possible ground invasion. 

The bombardment already has killed about 1,800 people in Gaza, including U.N. workers, paramedics and journalists.

"Rossa Palestina" is a song by the Italian musician and songwriter Pino Daniele, not to be confused with the Italian Pro-Palestinian song "Bella Ciao," which has been widely associated with various social and political movements.

Pino Daniele's "Rossa Palestina" is known for its pro-Palestinian message. Pino Daniele was an influential Italian singer-songwriter and guitarist who often incorporated social and political themes into his music. "Rossa Palestina" was released in 2005 on his album titled "Amore senza fine." The song's lyrics express solidarity with the Palestinian people and call for an end to violence and suffering in the region.

The song received attention for its political stance and was part of the broader international discourse regarding the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. It's an example of how music can be used to convey political messages and raise awareness about global issues.

The Israeliâ€“Palestinian conflict has its roots in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, with the birth of major nationalist movements among the Jews and among the Arabs, both geared towards attaining sovereignty for their people in the Middle East. The Balfour Declaration was a public statement issued by the British government in 1917 during the First World War announcing support for the establishment of a "national home for the Jewish people" in Palestine. The collision between those two movements in southern Levant upon the emergence of Palestinian nationalism after the Franco-Syrian War in the 1920s escalated into the Sectarian conflict in Mandatory Palestine in 1930s and 1940s, and expanded into the wider Arabâ€“Israeli conflict later on.
